description.text:
I have a projector set up and most equipment hooked up to it is fairly out of reach. It hasn't been an issue so far since I would only infrequently reach up to change a disc. However, with the Switch needing to dock to charge and how often I switch between docked gameplay and handheld, it became quite bothersome. So I designed this mount to hold the dock onto a wall.

It's held up by 3 screws. It allows you to remove the dock without removing the mount, if necessary. There is room both on the sides and in the back for proper venting. The mount seems to adequately hold the dock and Switch weight with no concern. With my design you do lose the bottom side USB port and LED indicator. These were of no concern to me so I made no effort to work around them, but if there's enough interest, I suppose I could just snip part of that side out. However, I'm sure it would be easy to do on one's own as well.

As a disclaimer, I am no expert engineer so although there doesn't seem to be any issues with my print, I can't guarantee your Switch won't get scratched or fall to a horrible death suddenly.

Hope you enjoy.

It was designed for this module but the others in the series seem to be the same sizes.
Total dimensions of the box are 120 x 80 x 80mm. 4mm banana plugs are used for the input and output with an additional hole for an XT60 output plug.

The rear panel is a simple piece that clips into place so no screws required. It also contains a duct for the fan. Nothing is attached to the rear panel so it can all be assembled inside the main box then the cover clipped on the back.

description.text:
I was trying to work out how small an item my printer (The awesome Prusa i3 MK2) was able to reliably produce that was able to clip on to another with the initial idea of making a fiddle toy that acted a little like cloth. It turned out that the printer could print even smaller than this reliably, but the material strength tended to be the weak point.

Every time I printed a sheet of these clips it would be taken away by the kids to play with, so I decided to put it on Thingiverse for other people to play with too!

Disclaimer

(and possibly shameless advert)
Your first layer and the accuracy of your printer is critical to the successful printing of this item at the given scale (Each piece is 8.5mm on the longest side).
I would suggest you start with the pair or the 4x4 version. The Prusa does it with no sweat, but if you're unable to print it successfully, try scale it up a little. Once you've got it perfect, print the 10x10 version for maximum clippy fun!

Suggestion: Print several different sheets in different colours, then mix and match to make patterns! It is also possible and fun to make block shapes if you fold up the sides and clip it together as a square tube.

description.text:
I recently built a Mechanical counter really just to discover how it actually worked, so with the ‘How it works’ theme in mind this project looks at how a simple lock works. Normally a Mortise lock fitted into a door will have a latch which is opened by turning the door handle and a Deadbolt that can be locked or opened with a key. For the purpose of this project I have removed the latch and use just a single lever to lock the bolt.
I have fitted this into the lid of a container so that you finish up with a lockable container for keeping small items secure.
In the picture shown the Bolt is Green and the Lever is red, when the key is fitted and turned, it firstly lifts the lever from its locking engagement with the bolt and continued turning then moves the bolt to its lock position. The Cap can now be rotated 30° anti-clockwise and pulled from the container.
The Lever has now been updated to include the cutout through the pivot hole

description.text: This remix breaks the body of the original Soprano Ukulele made by 3DGuy (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:162309) into four parts that are joined by dovetail joints, and then uses the rest of the pieces generated by Sound in his remix (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:199298). This was necessary for me, because unlike Sound, I don't have the extended length bed on my MendelMax 1.5. :-) It may also be of interest to some that this Ukulele was printed in PLA, and seems to work quite nicely.

As I mentioned, I used PLA, and as a material it seems fine for making a plastic ukulele.  I also used a Hilbert curve infill pattern, in an effort to avoid warp-induced peeling on the corners.  That plus a bit of a brim on the pieces with sharp corners (the top pieces especially) seems to have come out quite well on my heated-bed but not enclosed printer.  The pieces are held together with superglue, and retain the little index peg holes that Sound added to the model so that the pieces can be lined up.  3mm filament should fit in them.

comments.text: Hello, I was trying to print this on a Replicator 2. I am having problems with the neck, it seems that top corner keeps lifting off the bed. Do you have any advice on what to do to prevent this problem? I am using a glass bed and large masking tape on top. This is the largest print I've done on this MakerBot, but this is also the first time that this problem has happened. I attempted to print on rafts but the rafts don't fit on the bed towards the corners. Help?
comments.author: mercedesyortiz

comments.text: Yes, the neck is a tough print for warp. On a Rep2 you don't have much room for a brim or sidewalk so it's super important to maximize your stick! I used to print with blue tape, and was able to get that to work. Now (on all printers, including my Rep2) I print on a glass bed with Aquanet extra super hold. Start with at least three thick layers of Aquanet. Let each dry in between applications. Then, make sure that your bed is super level. As your print starts, watch your first layer to see that you are getting the right amount of squish. You can even adjust the bed level by hand as the first layer prints. If your beads of extrusion aren't squished enough and you've already printed either end (where warp is likely) -- cancel the print and start over!
comments.author: mercedesyortiz

comments.text: In addition to the masking tape, you might try a thin application of a glue stick where the corner issue is happening. Also there are "sidewalks" (one-layer extensions on the first layer) you can turn on in Makerbot Desktop.

description.text:
A camera case and arm to attach the innards of a Microsoft HD3000 to a Prusa i3 MK2 bed for smoother time lapses.

Uses a wide angle lens that can be found on ebay/amazon.
The one I got: http://www.ebay.com/itm/252732341201

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

ABS or other high temp material only!

I used Orange Zortrax z-abs @ 250C. The color is not a perfect match to the original Prusa orange but very close.

Only the arm needs supports.

Due to the design of the arm I had to reduce the print speed to about 25% of that of the case and lid.

Prepare

Make sure there is no oozing or anything to block the snap-fit

Make sure the original screws fit in the screw holes for the pcb

Make sure the arm fits (tightly) in the body.

Make sure the lens screws in snugly

Assembly

  1. Disassemble the HD3000 and keep the screws!
    I found a video of this: youtu.be/n6TQJI4boC0?t=6m22s

  2. Cut off the original body, I used side-cutters. Be careful of the wires!

  3. Desolder/ cut of the 3 cables for the build in mic. (you can maybe stash it inside the case, I don't know).

  4. Screw down the pcb into the case.

  5. Push the old cable relief into the hole for it.

  6. Push in the arm.

  7. Put on the lid.

  8. Guide the cable in the grove

  9. Screw on the lens

  10. Stick it on a standoff for the bed on the printer and tie the cable to the bed frame.

title: Adjustable Standpipe Funnel for Bell Siphon

description.text:
In aquaponics systems, a common way of irrigating beds is to use flood and drain using a bell siphon. For the bell siphon to work properly, the water must flow into the standpipe equally on all sides. This is a problem is the standpipe is either not completely perpendicular or the face is angled. The picture above of the raw standpipe shows the problem. When this happens, the siphon may not reliably start.

This thing is a ball and socket adapter that allows you to adjust the funnel so that water flows equally on all sides. It is also tapered which promotes proper autosiphoning behavior. There are two versions for 3/4" and 1" standpipes.

The funnel ball just snaps into the pivot base.

description.text: Mostly for testing X/Y/Z calibration.  The internal side-to-side vanes don't connect properly, and there were a few strings between the internal cylinders, but this mounts firmly on a real 2x4 brick.  Although I have "brim" turned off, the first layer of the brick oozes out a little bit beyond the intended spot, so you have to trim the bottom (top) of the brick to get it to fit cleanly between real bricks.

I had an Anet A8 Printer and this Printer really good for the price, but I wanted a better printing quality and a bigger heatbed. So took some 2020 aluminium profiles and printed a lot of parts.
Now I have a really nice and good working printer.
I Used following printed parts:
Y-Axis: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2140441
X-Axis: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1718315
E3D holder X- Axis: http://plastikjunkies.de/e3d-v6-elegance-transporteur-prusa-i3-anet-a8
Motor mount E3D: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1477900
Anti wobble: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1858435

For the Z-Axis upper and lower I changed this part: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2078215
For printing easily mirror the Z-axis parts to get left and right parts.

If you can understand german you can find a detailed description on http://plastikjunkies.de/anet-a8-umbau-auf-2020-profilrahmen/
inclusive all parts an some more pics.

My printer is almost finished (you ever change minor things) and the printing qualiy
is much better than before. And it fits into the Ikea Lack table system like before.

Here you find some remixed parts: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2251134
